Electrocatalytic synthesis of H2O2 via the oxygen electrochemistry has been widely considered as an attractive route for on-site production of H2O2. Such an approach has effectively addressed the disadvantages of the AQ process and the possibility to be coupled with sustainable energy sources [50, 51]. Note that there are two direct pathways to produce H2O2, including two-electron oxygen reduction reaction (2e− ORR, Fig. 2d) and two-electron water oxidation reaction (2e− WOR, Fig. 2e) [52–54]. As for the 2e− ORR process, the reduction of O2 to H2O2 proceeds by a two-step consecutive reaction road. This process can be described as an overall electrochemical reaction (Eq. 7), where Eθ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
